      <bioghist id="aspace_39428a5998df984b275f9e30ed7158ec">
         <head>Imperial British East Africa Company</head>
         <p>The Imperial British East Africa Company (IBEAC) was a commercial association founded to advance African trade in areas occupied by the British Empire. The company was incorporated and granted a royal charter by Queen Victoria in 1888. Led by Scottish shipping merchant Sir William Mackinnon, IBEAC administered the eastern coast of Africa from modern-day Somalia to modern-day Kenya. The company was also tasked with overseeing construction of a railway connecting the east coast region of Mombasa to Lake Victoria. IBEAC began building the Mackinnon-Sclater road, a 600-mile ox-cart track from Mombasa to Busia, Kenya, in 1890, and conducted surveys and expeditions into Uganda, but never commenced work on the railroad. The company began to fail financially, and the British government assumed administration of IBEAC's territory, which was divided to form the Uganda Protectorate in 1894 and East Africa Protectorate (later Kenya) in 1895. The Uganda Railway was completed by the government in 1901.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_2c86071c5e2620d6be846c5a11415dba">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Imperial British East Africa Company Papers. James Marshall and Marie-Louise Osborn Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_e556673b815603d733386063c6a2e6a3">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected.  The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>This collection received a basic level of processing, including rehousing and minimal organization.</p>
         <p>Information included in the Description of Papers note and Collection Contents section is drawn from information supplied with the collection and from an initial survey of the contents. Folder titles appearing in the contents list below are often based on those provided by the creator or previous custodian. Titles have not been verified against the contents of the folders in all cases. Otherwise, folder titles are supplied by staff during initial processing.</p>
         <p>This finding aid may be updated periodically to account for new acquisitions to the collection and/or revisions in arrangement and description.</p>
      </processinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_308c1080e7656f1cb8d37296a97f69c7">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of correspondence and printed material documenting activities of the British Imperial East Africa Company (IBEAC) and its chairman, Scottish businessman William Mackinnon. Included are letterbooks, reports, pamphlets, and other materials concerning the company's early negotiations with Zanzibar respecting land, taxes, mineral rights, and other matters; general administration of IBEAC's territory; and efforts to develop a railway from Mombasa to Victoria Lake. Letters and reports additionally detail initial scouting of locations for company stations and interactions of company representatives with the Maasai people. Among the correspondents and authors are Barghash ibn Sa'id, the Sultan of Zanzibar, Captain Frederick Lugard, and IBEAC administrator George Mackenzie. The collection additionally contains letter books documenting Mackinnon's earlier work as co-founder of the British India Steam Navigation Company and director of the City of Glasgow Bank.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_f36a96a0d39357d3fdf1fe89a3cfa408">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The Imperial British East Africa Company Papers is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.</p>
      </userestrict>
